Doping in sports.
The term "peptide" has been incorrectly or unclearly used to mean "illegal secretagogue" and "peptide hormones" in sports doping matters: 
illegal secretagogue peptides are classified as Schedule 2 (S2) prohibited substances on the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) Prohibited List, and are therefore prohibited for use by professional athletes both in and out of competition. Such peptide secretagogues have been on the WADA prohibited substances list since at least 2008. The Australian Crime Commission (incorrectly using the term "peptides") cited the alleged misuse of illegal peptide secretagogues used in Australian sport including growth hormone releasing peptides CJC-1295, GHRP-6, and GHSR (gene) hexarelin. There is ongoing controversy on the legality of using peptide secretagogues in sports.

